    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-30T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-30T06:00:00-05:00" n="817"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d817">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12623: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-30T20:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 30, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 30—10:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>904. I am informed orally that in the course of an interview granted yesterday by
                    the Prime Minister to Mr. Neukeu [<hi rend="italic">Menken?</hi>],
                    representative of Paramount News Company, Prince Konoye stated that Japan would
                    be able to reconcile the Tripartite Pact and the Neutrality <pb facs="0998"
                        n="990" xml:id="pg_990"/> Treaty with Soviet Russia. He said further that
                    while he foresaw a German victory and German domination of the western part of
                    Soviet Russia, he did not expect that German influence would extend to the east
                    and he thought that there might not be a collapse of the present Soviet regime.
                    He is reported to have emphasized that Japan desired only friendly relations
                    with the United States and that there was no reason for a conflict to arise
                    between the two countries.<note n="7" xml:id="d817fn7">See also memorandum by
                        Mr. Joseph W. Ballantine, June 30, <ref target="#pg_285">p.
                        285</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The representatives of the Associated Press and United Press, who were informed
                    of this interview, are of the opinion that in view of Prince Konoye’s reported
                    remarks it is improbable that the Japanese Government will issue any formal
                    statement of policy in the near future.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
